<H3> <TI>   President Meets With Iraqi Information Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Meets With Iraqi Information Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1804115094 Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network in 
Arabic 1030 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1804115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Djibouti President Hassan Gouled received this 
morning Hamid Yusuf Hammadi, minister of culture and information 
and President Saddam Husayn's envoy, who conveyed to him a 
personal message from the leader president. The message spells 
out Iraq's view of the position of the Security Council and the 
importance of activating this position to lift the unjust Iraq 
embargo, as well as the need to coordinate between friendly and 
brotherly countries toward this end. 
  The president of Djibouti asked the personal envoy to convey 
his brotherly greetings to leader President Saddam Husayn, as 
well as Djibouti's solidarity with Iraq and its constant call 
for lifting the unjust Iraq embargo. 
  Gouled stressed that Djibouti's position at the Security 
Council will be in favor of Iraq, especially since Iraq has 
fulfilled its obligations under Section C of Resolution 687. 
  The Iraqi envoy discussed with President Gouled ways to 
enhance brotherly relations between the two countries, including 
activating their joint committee. President Gouled said he had 
issued instructions in this regard. 
  Hamid Yusuf Hammadi met earlier with Mohamed Bolok Abdou, 
the 
foreign minister of Djibouti. During the meeting, they 
discussed the Security Council position. 
  The Iraqi envoy met also with Barkat Gourad Hamadou, the 
prime minister of Djibouti. They discussed ways to enhance 
relations between the two brotherly countries. 
  The Iraqi envoy then met with (Ismail Omar Ghila), chief of 
the Djibouti Presidential Court. They discussed the position of 
other nations toward lifting the unjust Iraq embargo, as well as 
bilateral relations. 

</TEXT>

