<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mwinyi To Host Rwandan Government, RPF Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1804214494 Dar es Salaam Radio Tanzania Network in Swahili 
1700 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1804214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Dar es Salaam Radio Tanzania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Swahili </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] President Ali Hassan Mwinyi will convene peace 
talks in Arusha to be attended by the Rwandan Government and 
rebels of the Rwanda Patriotic Front [RPF] on 23 April. 
  A statement issued by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and 
International Cooperation said the meeting was called following 
a deterioration of the war situation between the Government of 
Rwanda and RPF fighters, and as part of UN efforts to bring 
about a ceasefire. Tanzania has been involved in reconciling 
the two sides for a long period, culminating in the signing of a 
peace accord last year. [passage omitted] 
  The statement by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and 
International Cooperation said the government had received 
unconfirmed reports of the death of three Tanzanians. The 
statement also stated that the government was continuing with 
arrangements to repatriate Tanzanians currently in Rwanda [words 
indistinct] 
  The government also called on the Government of Rwanda to 
immediately release 44 vehicles and the goods in them. The 
vehicles belong to Tanzanians and have been held at the border. 
In the meantime, the Kagera regional commissioner, Honorable 
Phillip Mangula, has said that six UN soldiers have entered the 
Mara Region from Rwanda and that they are being looked after by 
the UN High Commissioner on Refugees. 

</TEXT>

