<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Announce Political Agenda in Jan 1995 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Announce Political Agenda in Jan 1995 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1904101594 Kaduna Radio Nigeria in English 0900 GMT 19 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1904101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kaduna Radio Nigeria </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Federal Government is to announce its political 
agenda in January next year. The minister of information, 
Professor Jerry Gana, made this known yesterday while briefing 
newsmen in Lagos. Prof. Gana explained that January was chosen 
to give the delegates at the national constitutional conference 
enough time to finish their deliberations. The announcement, 
according to him, will be the climax of phase two of the 
government's political agenda, which started with the 
constitutional conference. The minister said the government 
would not want to give a specific date for the handover because 
it did not know the regulations or the structure the conference 
would want the nation to take. Prof. Gana, however, noted that 
the constitutional conference, which was the first phase of the 
political agenda, would not go beyond December this year. He 
said the election of delegates to the conference will start in 
the first week of June, while the conference will convene on 27 
June in Abuja. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

