<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beye Meets With Government, UNITA Delegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beye Meets With Government, UNITA Delegations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1804203694 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1804203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Manuel da Conceicao in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] The government and National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola [UNITA] teams to the Lusaka peace talks 
were scheduled to meet today, but that did not happen because it 
was only today that the mediators delivered the intermediate 
document on specific principles, modalities for their 
implementation, and the conclusion of the electoral process. 
  UNITA handed its proposal over to the mediators on 15 April. 
The government did the same the next day. This morning, UN 
Special Representative Alioune Blondin Beye held separate 
meetings -- first with the government team and then with the 
UNITA delegation. The observers attended both meetings, where 
Blondin Beye delivered a document reflecting the mediators' 
views regarding the proposals advanced by the government and by 
UNITA. 
  No meetings were held this afternoon. The negotiating teams 
took time off to reflect on the document and suggest possible 
amendments. The UN special representative is scheduled to meet 
with the two sides tomorrow to get their responses. Should 
there not be too many differences, Blondin Beye is likely to 
call for a face-to-face meeting between the government and UNITA 
teams. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

