<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IEC on Arrangements for Voting Stations Security </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IEC on Arrangements for Voting Stations Security </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1904083994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0656 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1904083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement issued by the IEC on the SAPA PR Wire Service on </F>
18 April] 
  [Text] The IEC [Independent Electoral Commission] met today 
with all security structures to finalise plans for securing 
voting stations. The final number of venues for voting stations 
will be approximately 8,200, because there can be more than one 
voting station at a single venue. The SAP [South African 
Police] have conveyed that they will be able to secure this 
number of venues. 
  Certain problem areas remain, such as Lebowa, Ciskei, Soweto 
and Athlone in the Cape. The IEC has planned specific meetings 
with the regional offices of the SAP, and SADF [South African 
Defense Force], and local police forces where relevant. It is 
hoped to resolve these issues by Wednesday. 
  The SADF will act as support to the SAP, and where the 
deployment of SAP forces is insufficient, the SADF presence will 
become more visible. 
  The Transkei police force will be patrolling voting stations 
in the Transkei. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

