<H3> <TI>   NPKF, Thokoza Hostel Inmates Exchange Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPKF, Thokoza Hostel Inmates Exchange Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    East Rand Hostels To Be Reinforced </H4>

<F P=102> MB1904090694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0848 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1904090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by K. Swart] </F>
  [Text] Johannesburg April 19 SAPA -- Hundreds of West Rand 
hostel residents would be transported to the East Rand to 
reinforce hostels "under attack" by the National Peacekeeping 
Force [NPKF], the National Hostel Residents Association [NHRA] 
said on Tuesday. 
  NHRA spokesman Thulani Mlothshwa said: "Let the world know 
more militants will be deployed on the East Rand and they will 
be told to take no nonsense from the NPKF who, with township 
residents, attacked our hostel yesterday (Monday)." 
  He was referring to a gunfight between NPKF and Thokoza 
hostel residents on Monday which resulted in the death of news 
photographer Ken Oostebroek. 
  Mr Mlotshwa said the deployment of the NPKF had given a 
boost 
to the enemies of hostel residents. "They thought it would now 
be easier to attack the hostels. This was proved yesterday 
(Monday) when township residents came in large numbers, 
accompanied by NPKF members, to attack the Thokoza hostel. As a 
result the hostel inmates were forced to defend themselves." 
  Hostel residents were protected by their own "military" and 
500 reinforcements from West Rand hostels would be brought in to 
protect East Rand hostels from attack. "We would like to warn 
all those who are still prepared to attack the hostels that if 
they think they are militant, they will find us more militant," 
Mr Mlotshwa said. 

</TEXT>

