<H3> <TI>   NPKF, Thokoza Hostel Inmates Exchange Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPKF, Thokoza Hostel Inmates Exchange Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    NPKF Reportedly Requests SAP Help </H4>

<F P=102> MB1904130494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1212 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1904130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg April 19 SAPA -- Police on Tuesday said 
the Internal Stability Division [ISD] had not returned to 
Thokoza on the East Rand where soldiers of the National 
Peacekeeping Force [NPKF], hostel and township residents fought 
running gun battles through the day. 
  Police East Rand spokesman Lt Deon Peens told SAPA police 
were not intervening in the conflict. "The ISD was not back 
there. Police are doing normal police work, driving around in 
their bakkies [pickup trucks]," he said. He confirmed the NPKF 
had requested the assistance of the South African Police [SAP], 
and directed all enquiries to the NPKF head office. 
  An NPKF soldier could not confirm a report that the force 
had 
fired a mortar round into Hostel No 2 in the township. He said 
it was "very, very busy" in Thokoza. 
  Inkatha Freedom Party Spokesman Ed Tillet said: "The NKPF 
are totally out of control. They are firing indiscriminately at 
everyone." Mr Tillet said the car in which IFP Transvaal 
Political Director Themba Khoza was travelling in the township 
had been petrol bombed, but this had yet to be confirmed. 
  Police were on Tuesday investigating a rocket-propelled 
grenade attack on No 2 Hostel in Thokoza. A police spokesman 
said the RPG7 attack caused little damage and no one was 
injured. Three people were killed earlier in the day and 
several others injured in crossfire between township residents 
and hostel residents, police said. 

</TEXT>

