<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Goldstone Commission Holds Hearing on Zulu March </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Goldstone Commission Holds Hearing on Zulu March </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Preliminary Hearing Begins </H4>

<F P=102> MB1804101294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0947 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1804101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by A. Quintal] </F>
  [Text] Johannesburg April 18 SAPA -- The preliminary 
hearing of the Goldstone Commission into the Zulu march through 
Johannesburg on March 28 began at the commission's Sandton 
offices on Monday morning. The march resulted in 53 deaths and 
more than 200 injured. 
  The South African Police [SAP], the Inkatha Freedom Party 
[IFP] and the kwaZulu government will make their submissions to 
the commission on Monday and Tuesday. 
  The SAP, represented by Mr B. Roux, handed in a bulky 
document detailing the police version of events. Mr Roux told 
the commission that, contrary to newspaper reports, the IFP had 
applied to the Johannesburg City Council for permission to hold 
an anti-election meeting at Library Gardens, and not a march. 
Permission for the meeting had been granted. Mr Roux stressed 
the police had had no idea before the meeting that snipers would 
gun down Zulus on city streets. 
  Mr Maurice Basslian is representing the kwaZulu government 
and the IFP, and Mr George Bizos the African National Congress. 
The hearing is being attended by observers from Jamaica, 
Germany, Great Britain and the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

