<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Goldstone Commission Holds Hearing on Zulu March </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Goldstone Commission Holds Hearing on Zulu March </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Goldstone Rejects IFP Explanation </H4>

<F P=102> MB1904082294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0755 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1904082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by A. Quintal] </F>
  [Text] Johannesburg April 19 SAPA -- The Inkatha Freedom 
Party's [IFP] explanation of its failure to submit evidence to 
the Goldstone Commission of inquiry into the violence during the 
Zulu march in Johannesburg on March 28 was "wholly 
unacceptable", Mr Justice Richard Goldstone said on Tuesday. 
  KwaZulu government and IFP legal representative Mr Maurice 
Basslian told the commission the IFP had been unable to make 
submissions because of April's public holidays, the lack of 
manpower and records and the problem of finding witnesses. 
  Mr Justice Goldstone dismissed the explanation as 
unacceptable, especially as the IFP had requested the probe as a 
matter of urgency on March 29. He said other parties had made 
their submission in spite of the public holidays. While he 
could understand the difficulty of consulting witnesses, the IFP 
leaders at least could have given instruction, he said. 
  Following the explanation, the IFP made a submission which 
Mr 
Basslian stressed had been prepared in haste. 

</TEXT>

