<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SAP Advises Public To Disregard Rumors of Shortages </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1904092194 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0910 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1904092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by N. Lewis] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria April 19 SAPA -- The South African Police 
[SAP] on Tuesday [19 April] appealed to the public to disregard 
alarmist rumours about impending widespread violence, food 
shortages and similar speculation in the run-up to the elections. 
  It said it was aware of the rumours and a growing number of 
facsimile messages urging the public to take special 
precautions. "It is in our best interest that we remain calm and 
rational. The SAP requests the public to disregard 
irresponsible, inaccurate rumours. There are assurances from 
many companies that the services they provide will continue to 
be provided during the election period." 

